                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d421">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.6176/23: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-28T16:00:00+01:19"
                            >September 28, 1936—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 28—12:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Department’s telegram 27, September 24, 5 p.m. Department’s instruction
                    carried out. Professor Van Gelderen of the Ministry of the Colonies has just
                    telephoned before leaving for London that (1) he agrees in principle with our
                    point of view, (2) the Netherlands Government remains unalterably opposed to
                    excessive prices or fluctuations, (3) he does not believe we should be too
                    anxious about acts of Rubber Committee although he cannot even informally make
                    any statement to me as to the future policy of the Committee.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
